{{distinguish|Thomas Williams, 1st Baron Williams|Thomas Williams (UK politician)}}
{{otherpersons|Tom Williams}}
'''(Thomas) "Tom" Williams, Baron Williams of Barnburgh''', [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] ([[18 March]] [[1888]] &ndash; [[29 March]] [[1967]]) was a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]]. 

Born in [[Blackwell, Derbyshire]], Williams grew up in [[Swinton, South Yorkshire|Swinton in Yorkshire]], and began work in 1899 in [[Kilnhurst]].  He became involved in [[trade unionism]] and joined the [[Independent Labour Party]], joining the [[British Socialist Party]] briefly during [[World War I]].  In 1918, he was elected as a Labour member of the [[Bolton-upon-Dearne]] [[Urban District Council]].

He was elected at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1922|1922 general election]] as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Don Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Don Valley]], and held the seat until he stepped down at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1959|1959 general election]].

In [[Winston Churchill]]'s [[World War II|wartime]] [[Coalition Government 1940-1945|Coalition Government]], he was [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries]] from [[1940]] to [[1945]], serving under the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] minister [[Robert Hudson, 1st Viscount Hudson|Robert Hudson]]. He was made a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] in [[1941]].  In [[Clement Attlee]]'s post-war [[Labour Government 1945-1951|Labour government]], he was [[Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]] from 1945 to [[1951]].

After his retirement from the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] in [[1959]], he was made a [[life peer]] in February [[1961]] as '''Baron Williams of Barnburgh''', of [[Barnburgh]] in the West Riding of [[Yorkshire]].

